    image: "https://storage.mlcdn.com/account_image/226112/oJwooxXLdoigeh1EfKB05UVz6G2PDrDR4Dba7xdY.png",
    content: `The ErasmusPlus KA220 Cooperation Project, coordinated by Tribeka Training lab, has released its initial findings. These are accessible at www.piramiderasmusplus.eu in various languages.

Project collaborators examined survey results aimed at identifying obstacles faced by students, instructors, and businesses when engaging across cultural lines. Using the Richard D. Lewis Model for cultural classification, the research investigated three domains:

Students encountered difficulties during peer interactions with individuals from different cultures, both in academic and overseas internship settings.

Teachers faced challenges when supervising or assessing students of varied nationalities, particularly when adaptation problems emerged.

Host Companies struggled with managing trainees, workers, or clientele from diverse cultural backgrounds, notably in hospitality and tourism industries.

The survey uncovered noteworthy patterns between responses and Lewis's cultural categories, deepening understanding of intercultural interactions in these contexts.

The team created the P.iR.A.M.iD. Theoretical Model, which modifies Lewis's framework for today's multicultural work environment. The model applies Lewis's three cultural classifications—Linear-Active, Reactive, and Multi-Active—across tourism, education, and digital sectors.

Linear-Active professionals demonstrate methodical approaches, precision, and emotional restraint. Reactive individuals emphasize listening, diplomatic communication, and relationship-building. Multi-Active participants lead discussions, adjust flexibly, and communicate with expressive engagement.

These findings represent preliminary steps toward creating practical resources and strategies for educational institutions, organizations, and professionals operating in multicultural contexts, underscoring how essential intercultural skills have become.`
